<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: 3 FLORIDA AREAS ON NATIONAL LEAGUE EXPANSION 'SHORT LIST' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Six cities, including three from Florida, were chosen Tuesday as finalists for 
two National League expansion franchises that will begin play in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
The candidates are Buffalo, Denver, Miami, Orlando, St. Petersburg-Tampa and 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
Eliminated were Nashville, Tenn.; Charlotte, N.C.; Phoenix and Sacramento, 
along with other ownership groups in several of the cities selected. 
</P>
<P>
"It's been a long time coming," said Ron Safford, director of sports 
development for the Florida Department of Commerce. "Regardless of what cities 
are selected, Florida is the ultimate winner. We now feel we have a 50-50 shot, 
with half the teams on the list." 
</P>
<P>
Final selection of the two franchises is expected before the end of September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
