</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A crash involving at least 10 vehicles, including two Greyhound buses, on a 
highway shrouded by a severe desert sandstorm today injured more than a dozen 
people, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
The crash occurred about 11 a.m. near Yermo, about 10 miles north of Barstow on 
Interstate 15, the main route between Los Angeles and Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
Gale-force winds, reportedly near 50 m.p.h., had whipped up a furious sandstorm 
that had reduced visibility to five feet or less, California Highway Patrol 
Sgt. J. D. Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
Two Greyhound buses, a semi-truck and at least seven other vehicles, all 
traveling north toward Las Vegas, were involved in the crash. 
</P>
<P>
Three major injuries were reported to passengers aboard one of the buses. At 
least 10 other people riding in the other vehicles also suffered major 
injuries. 
</P>
