<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
U.S. OIL DEMAND FALLS OFF 2.6% 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Overall U.S. oil demand dropped 2.6% in November from year-ago levels in face 
of higher fuel prices and the slowing economy, the American Petroleum Institute 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
The United States is the world's largest oil-consuming nation and the No. 2 oil 
producer after the Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
Demand for most major petroleum products, such as gasoline and home-heating 
oil, declined in November, the oil industry trade group said in its monthly 
report, but deliveries of kerosene jet fuel reached record levels for this time 
of year. 
</P>
<P>
Domestic crude production slipped 6% in November from a year ago, partly 
reflecting an ouptut slowdown from Alaska's North Slope caused by stormy 
weather at the Port of Valdez. 
</P>
